{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A file placed inside a subdirectory of the watched root is processed, not only files placed directly in the root directory.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA and SYSTEM TRIAD apply: this behavior depends on real OS filesystem watcher recursion and proving an externally visible side effect (file dropped under a real subdirectory is actually processed end-to-end). Unit/integration fakes can miss watcher-recursion and event-delivery differences.","test_description":"Start the daemon against a real temp watched root and real output dir. Create a nested subdirectory, write a file into it, and assert via round-trip readback that exactly one transformed output artifact appears for that nested file.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.17,"System":0.78,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The deduplication logic correctly discards a second processing request for the same file path within a configurable time window.","required_reality_check_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS is cross-component handoff/state, not pure single-function math: evidence phrase is \"second processing request for the same file path within a configurable time window\" (request intake + config + shared dedupe state). REAL-INFRA not required by text; this can be validated in-process. Rejected System because behavior text does not require real OS/network/subprocess contract checks or external round-trip effects.","test_description":"Wire intake -> dedupe -> enqueue/processor modules in-process with a controllable clock. Submit two requests for the same path within the configured window and assert only one reaches processing; advance time beyond window and assert a new request is accepted.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the operating system emits multiple filesystem events for a single file write, the daemon processes the file exactly once.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"Behavior explicitly names OS event semantics (\"operating system emits multiple filesystem events\"), so REAL-INFRA is required. In-process fakes can hide duplicate-event patterns from real watchers. Also requires externally visible once-only effect.","test_description":"Run daemon against a real watched directory. Perform a write pattern that triggers multiple FS events on the host OS (e.g., temp-write+rename or chunked write), then assert only one output/result is produced for that file path.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.93,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"If the watched directory is removed and then recreated while the daemon is running, the daemon resumes watching the new directory without a restart.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"Requires real OS filesystem lifecycle behavior (directory deletion/recreation while watcher is live) and round-trip proof that new files are processed after recreation. Unit/integration tests cannot fully surface watcher rebind behavior.","test_description":"Start daemon on a real directory, then delete and recreate that directory while process stays running. Add a new file to the recreated directory and assert it is processed successfully without restarting the daemon.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.92,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When multiple files arrive at the same time, they are processed in the order determined by their creation timestamps.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"Ordering here depends on real arrival